The [Attention mechanism](<https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Attention_(machine_learning)>) was first proposed in the visual field. In 2014, Google Mind published "Recurrent Models of Visual Attention", which made the Attention mechanism popular. This paper uses the RNN model and adds the Attention mechanism to classify images. In 2015, in the paper "Neural Machine Translation by Jointly Learning to Align and Translate", Bahdanau et al. applied the attention mechanism to the nlp field for the first time. They used the Seq2Seq+Attention model for machine translation, and the effect was improved. Seq2Seq Introduced in With Attention. In 2017, the "Attention is All You Need" published by the Google machine translation team completely abandoned network structures such as RNN and CNN, and only used the Attention mechanism for machine translation tasks, and achieved good results.

### Related knowledge concepts

- [RNN](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/RNN)

  <img src="data:image/png;base64," />

  RNN(Recurrent Netural Network) is a network which used to process sequence data（Sequence Data has a characteristic - the latter data is related to the former data）.

  - RNN forword propagation: 

    ① S(t) = $s_{t}=\Phi (Ux_{t}+Ws_{t-1})$

    ②  O{t} = f(V\Phi (Ux_{t}+Ws_{t-1}))$

    * St is t hidden layer state；Ot is the output value at time t.
  ① Hidden Layer: U The weight matrix of the input x，St-1 is state of time t-1；Ot，W is the weight matrix of the input:St-1，$\Phi $ is the activation function；
  ② Output layer，V : The weight matrix of the output layer，f: activation function
    * loss function(cross entropy):$L_{t}=-\overline{o_{t}}logo_{_{t}}$（Ot is t prediction value，$\overline{o_{t}}$is t ground truth）
    * for a training task，loss: $L=\sum_{i=1}^{T}-\overline{o_{t}}logo_{_{t}}$， T is the sequence's length。

  - RNN back propagation: 

  - Vanishing Gradient Problem In RNN: The same optimization parameters in the RNN are shared at each time, and the final gradient g = sum（g_1,...,g_t) at each time step; compared to the output at a distant time, the calculation of the gradient requires more derivation operations , which makes the long-distance gradient more likely to disappear or explode. In other words, the total gradient in the RNN will not disappear, but the gradient corresponding to the long-distance output is more likely to disappear, making it difficult for the model to learn long-distance gradients.

- LSTM
  <br />
  The full name of LSTM is Long Short Term Memory networks, which is a special form
  of RNN, which is characterized by the ability to learn long-distance dependencies.LSTMs
  were developed to deal with the vanishing gradient problem.
- vanishing gradient problem
- GRU
- Word Embedding

  - Word2Vec
    Word2Vec is an efficient training word proposed by Tomas Mikolov et al. in the Google research team in "Distributed Representations of Words and Phrases and their Compositionality" in 2013 and the subsequent "Efficient Estimation of Word Representations in Vector Space". The basic starting point of the vector model is similar to the distributed representation: two words with similar contexts should have similar word vectors.

  - BERT
    (Bidirectional Encoder Representation from Transformers) BERT uses the Transformer Encoder block for connection, which is a typical two-way encoding model.
